  'sleep_disorder_reset',
  18,
  'Deep Sleep Optimization',
  'Day 18 - Deep Sleep Optimization',
  '',
  21,
  '[{"type":"intro","dayNumber":18,"dayTitle":"Deep Sleep Optimization","goal":"Complete Day 18 with steady, consistent action.","estimatedMinutes":21},{"type":"lesson","title":"Today''s Focus","paragraphs":["Complete Day 18 with steady, consistent action."],"highlight":"Consistency compounds into long-term change."},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":1,"title":"Morning Sunlight Exposure (10–20 Minutes)","instructions":["Within 30 minutes of waking, go outside and expose your eyes to natural daylight.","Step outside your home, balcony, or street.","Do not wear sunglasses.","Face the direction of the sky (not directly at the sun).","Stay outside for 10–20 minutes.","Combine sunlight exposure with 10 minutes of slow walking.","Why this works","Morning sunlight resets the brain’s circadian rhythm, helping regulate melatonin release at night."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"breathing_exercise","title":"Hydration + Nervous System Activation","instructions":"Immediately after sunlight, drink 500–700 ml of water. Then perform this breathing exercise. 10 Cycles of Physiological Sigh Inhale through nose Take a second short inhale Slowly exhale through mouth Repeat 10 times. This lowers stress hormones and relaxes the nervous system.","pattern":{"inhaleSeconds":4,"exhaleSeconds":6},"cycles":10},{"type":"exercise_routine","title":"Increased Morning Movement (sleep Pressure Builder)","exercises":[{"name":"Total Movement Time: 45 Minutes","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Exercise Routine","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Brisk Walking","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"25 Minutes Continuous Walking.","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Bodyweight Squats","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"30 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Pushups","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"20 Reps × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Jumping Jacks","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"55 Reps × 4 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"Plank Hold","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]},{"name":"45 Seconds × 5 Sets","instructions":["Perform with steady breathing and controlled pacing."]}]},{"type":"action_step","stepNumber":2,"title":"Caffeine Control Rule","instructions":["Follow this rule strictly:","No caffeine after 2 PM","This includes:","coffee","tea","energy drinks","pre-workout drinks","Caffeine can remain active in the body 6–8 hours, interfering with sleep quality."],"whyThisWorks":"Small consistent actions reinforce stability and reduce automatic, stress-driven reactions."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Evening Nervous System Downshift","steps":["About 60 minutes before bed, listen to your guided sleep meditation audio.","Lie comfortably in bed.","Play the meditation audio at low volume.","Close your eyes and follow the instructions.","Allow your body to relax naturally.","Recommended length: 10–20 minutes."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"Body Temperature Sleep Trick","steps":["Take a warm shower 60–90 minutes before sleep.","Why this works","After the shower, the body temperature drops slightly, signaling the brain that it is time for sleep."],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"mindfulness_exercise","title":"The Military Sleep Method (fast Sleep Technique)","steps":["Once in bed, do this:","Relax your forehead","Relax jaw and tongue","Drop shoulders completely","Slowly breathe out","Then imagine a calm scene:","You are lying beside a quiet lake under a moonlit sky.","The water is still and the air is peaceful.","Focus on the calm scene while breathing slowly.","Day 18 Sleep Trick – The “Eye Relaxation Method”","Eye tension can keep the brain in alert mode, especially after screen use.","While lying in bed:","Close your eyes gently.","Imagine your eyeballs sinking deeper into the eye sockets.","Let your eyes become very heavy and relaxed.","Stay with this feeling for 2–3 minutes.","Why this works","Relaxing the eye muscles signals the brain that alertness is no longer required, helping the nervous","system transition into sleep mode.","Day 18 Goal","Deepen physical and neurological relaxation, preparing the body for stronger deep sleep cycles.","By Day 18 many people notice:","falling asleep more quickly","deeper sleep stages","improved morning energy"],"completionMessage":"Stay with the practice until your body and mind feel steadier."},{"type":"journal","prompt":"What helped you most on Day 18?","helperText":"Write one or two practical observations.","followUpPrompt":"What will you repeat tomorrow?"},{"type":"close","message":"Day 18 is complete.","secondaryMessage":"You reinforced deep sleep optimization today."}]'::jsonb
)
